I don't think anyone expected you to buy into our beliefs about our families. When I posted the link to the submission article, I was merely hoping you would read it and respect that it is how some view their marriages. I never expected you to accept, agree, or understand it. I think by the same token, the women who posted the LDS stand on families (which I think sums it up pretty darn well even though I'm not LDS) also would merely ask for respect about their beliefs - not agreement or acceptance. You know, I don't understand why so many people (men and women) have such a hard time with women who WANT to stay home and raise their children. Take me for instance ... I'm quite educated (BA, teaching credential, Master's degree); heck, I teach part-time at a college. And yet, I choose to spend the majority of my time home with my son. There is no other place I would rather be, no other job I would rather have, than raising him, and I am so grateful that we are financially finally in a place where I can work as little as I do and still get by. But, I would never tell another woman that she must do the same. My cousin, for one, equally as educated, has decided to return to work and have her children in day care. Who am I to judge what she does? Who are you or anyone else to judge what I decide to do? I do not think I am mocking the equal rights advocates, nor am I not carrying my own weight (if you think staying home is a plush job, think again). My dh and I have chosen what works for our family. Yes, I wish all wives/moms had the same opportunity and desire - how wonderful for our children to be raised, 24 hours a day, by their mom (or dad) instead of another caregiver. I used to teach elementary school and the kids that had to go to daycare afterschool hated it. All they wanted was to go home - to their home. But, just because those parents, for whatever reason, chose otherwise, does not make them bad parents at all. Me choosing to stay home with my son does not make me a bad &quot;woman&quot; - I only ask that others respect my decisions as I respect theirs. <br>
