<br>
Do I think family is important?  Absolutely.  Do I claim that my family is somehow better because it fits a stereotype of a working dad, stay home mom, 1 ds, 1 dd and a dog?  Absolutely NOT!  I firmly believe that the values this society needs (integrity, work ethics, laughter, honor, tolerance, love etc) are best taught in the home.  I happen to think it's horrible that the state of Florida was trying to keep a gay couple from adopting the children they had raised from birth.  Whatever your family looks like, it is still the source of most of what our children will learn and hang on to as the grow.  Of course people can break away from disfunction (my mom is a prime example) and of course people will fall into it (my brother).   Yes, people will divorce, and remarry.  We'll always have abusers and victims.  But if we had strong family values, we might be able to raise children who can avoid abusive situations, etc.  <br>
<br>
If you must know, I do the finances in our home.  I also bring in a source of income (freelance photography and private piano lessons).  Dh and I share responsibilities around the house and with our kids.  We make decisions together.  I've never felt inferior to him.  What we believe works for us, and who are you to say we're wrong?<br>
